We are now in a position to notice, and with some attentive scrutiny, the eyrograph or agreement between the Abbey and the Priory. And, in the first place, I would draw attention to the terms employed in speak- ing of what the Priory was to cede at Thixendale. The words are “ et quatuor carucatas terrae in Sextendals, quas advocatus noster adhuc tenet in manu sua.” This last expression is entirely decisive as to the relative date of the document in question. Mr. Walbran writes, “There is no date to this very singular document, but some internal evidence appears to refer it to an early period in the thirteenth century,” while he also defines “ advocatus noster '’ as the “ common patron of the two houses, Lord de Ros, who, some people probably sus- pected, looked upon sweet Kirkham's lawn as a kind of Naboth’s vineyard from his dreary moorland eastle at Helmsley.’'

No one, I think, who takes the trouble to collate the passage just cited from the cyrograph of exchange with the contrasted extracts from the two Fundationes will be disposed to indorse Mr. Walbran's views, either as to the identity of the common patron, his motive, or the date of the “singular document ” itself.
